{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"1fa813cc-cfed-4845-9ba9-c9cf62664d28","content":"The project isn't in this workspace, but here's how to configure it. Create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for C# MCP servers using `ModelContextProtocol` / `Microsoft.Extensions.AI`).\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run` pointing at your `.csproj`.\n- For a **published** build, replace with `\"command\": \"path/to/MyMcpServer\"` and remove `args`.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat panel in agent mode (`@`), and your server's tools will be available.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c94d2629-441b-4b9e-b093-9cb31547ff43","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist at that path. The user said they built it there, but it's not present in the current working directory. That's fine — they're asking a \"how do I configure\" question, not asking me to modify their project. I can answer based on general knowledge.\n\nLet me give them the standard `mcp.json` configuration for a C# stdio MCP server used with VS Code agent mode.","outputTokens":360},"id":"46ab3f1f-2daf-4a99-a4a8-ca57b25fe629","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:50:55.570Z","parentId":"04afe4cc-176e-4eb7-b9a3-d6b10cdc5245"}
